# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: trade-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:trade-association/advertising] Commercial advertisements often seek to generate increased consumption of products or services through "branding", which associates a product name or image with certain qualities in the minds of consumers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising that intends to elicit an immediate sale is known as direct-response advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Non-commercial entities that advertise include political parties, interest groups, religious organizations, and governmental agencies.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Non-profit organizations may use free modes of persuasion, such as a public service announcement.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising may also help to reassure employees or shareholders that a company is viable or successful.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Worldwide spending on advertising was estimated to be over US$1 trillion in 2025.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising's distribution for 2024 was 59.4% on digital, 24.9% on TV, 5.2% on out-of-home, 4.5% on radio, 3.5% on newspapers, 2.2% on magazines and 0.4% on cinema.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Internationally, the largest advertising agency groups in 2025 were Omnicom, Publicis and WPP.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Egyptians used papyrus to make sales messages and wall posters.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Commercial messages and political campaign displays have been found in the ruins of Pompeii and ancient Arabia.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Lost and found advertising on papyrus was common in ancient Greece and ancient Rome.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Wall or rock painting for commercial advertising is another manifestation of an ancient advertising form, which is present to this day in many parts of Asia, Africa, and South America.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The tradition of wall painting can be traced back to Indian rock art paintings that date back to 4000 BC.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In ancient China, the earliest advertising recorded was in the Classic of Poetry (11th to 7th centuries BC) which describes bamboo flutes playing to sell confectionery.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising usually took the form of calligraphic signboards and inked papers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Fruits and vegetables were sold in the city square from carts and wagons and their proprietors used street callers (town criers) to announce their whereabouts.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The first compilation of such advertisements was gathered in "Les Crieries de Paris", a thirteenth-century poem by Guillaume de la Villeneuve.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By the end of the 18th century in England, the circulation of newspapers had increased and advertising accounted for a significant proportion of newspaper content.
[src:trade-association/advertising] As a result the word 'advertiser' began to be used in newspaper names/titles.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Prior to the 19th century, most advertisements were for books or medicines.
[src:trade-association/advertising] At this time it was rare for advertisements to use images.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the United States, newspapers grew quickly in the first few decades of the 19th century, in part due to advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By 1822, the United States had more newspaper readers than any other country.
[src:trade-association/advertising] About half of the content of these newspapers consisted of advertising, usually local advertising, with half of the daily newspapers in the 1810s using the word "advertiser" in their name.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In August 1859, British pharmaceutical firm Beechams created a slogan for Beecham's Pills: "Beechams Pills: Worth a guinea a box", which is considered to be the world's first advertising slogan.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The Beechams adverts would appear in newspapers all over the world, helping the company become a global brand.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The phrase was said to be uttered by a satisfied lady purchaser from St Helens, Lancashire, the founder's hometown.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In June 1836, the French newspaper *La Presse* was the first to include paid advertising in its pages, allowing it to lower its price, extend its readership and increase its profitability and the formula was soon copied by all titles.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Palmer established the roots of the modern day advertising agency in Philadelphia.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 1842 Palmer bought large amounts of space in various newspapers at a discounted rate then resold the space at higher rates to advertisers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The actual ad (copy, layout, and artwork) was prepared by the company advertising, with Palmer being a space broker.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The first full-service advertising agency of N.W.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Ayer & Son was founded in 1869 in Philadelphia.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Ayer & Son offered to plan, create, and implement complete advertising campaigns for its customers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By 1900 the advertising agency had become the focal point of creative planning, and advertising was firmly established as a profession.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Around the same time, in France, Charles-Louis Havas extended the services of his news agency, Havas to include advertisement brokerage.
[src:trade-association/advertising] At first, agencies were brokers for advertisement space in newspapers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The late 19th and early 20th centuries saw the rise of modern advertising, driven by industrialization and the growth of consumer goods.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This era saw the early ad agencies employing more cunning methods such as persuasive diction and psychological tactics.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Barratt of London has been called "the father of modern advertising".
[src:trade-association/advertising] Working for the Pears soap company, Barratt created an effective advertising campaign for the company products, which involved the use of targeted slogans, images, and phrases.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Have you used Pears' soap?" was famous in its day and into the 20th century.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 1882, Barratt recruited English actress and socialite Lillie Langtry to become the poster girl for Pears, making her the first celebrity to endorse a commercial product.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Becoming the company's brand manager in 1865, listed as the first of its kind by the *Guinness Book of Records*, Barratt introduced many of the crucial ideas that lie behind successful advertising, and these were widely circulated in his day.
[src:trade-association/advertising] He stressed the importance of a strong and exclusive brand image for Pears and of emphasizing the product's availability through saturation campaigns.
[src:trade-association/advertising] He also understood the importance of constantly reevaluating the market for changing tastes, stating in 1907 that "tastes change, fashions change, and the advertiser has to change with them.
[src:trade-association/advertising] An idea that was effective a generation ago would fall flat, stale, and unprofitable if presented to the public today.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Enhanced advertising revenues was one effect of the Industrial Revolution in Britain.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Thanks to the revolution and the consumers it created, by the mid-19th century biscuits and chocolate became products for the masses, and British biscuit manufacturers were among the first to introduce branding to distinguish grocery products.
[src:trade-association/advertising] One the world's first global brands, Huntley & Palmers biscuits were sold in 172 countries in 1900, and their global reach was reflected in their advertisements.
[src:trade-association/advertising] As a result of massive industrialization, advertising increased dramatically in the United States.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 1919, advertising expenditure was 2.5% of gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:trade-association/advertising] Industry could not benefit from its increased productivity without a substantial increase in consumer spending.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This contributed to the development of mass marketing designed to influence the population's economic behavior on a larger scale.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the 1910s and 1920s, advertisers in the U.S. adopted the doctrine that human instincts could be targeted and harnessed – "sublimated" into the desire to purchase commodities.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Edward Bernays, a nephew of Sigmund Freud, became associated with the method and is sometimes called the founder of modern advertising and public relations.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In other words, selling products by appealing to the rational minds of customers (the main method used prior to Bernays) was much less effective than selling products based on the unconscious desires that Bernays felt were the true motivators of human action.
[src:trade-association/advertising] "Sex sells" became a controversial issue, with techniques for titillating and enlarging the audience posing a challenge to conventional morality.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the 1920s, under Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover, the American government promoted advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Hoover himself delivered an address to the Associated Advertising Clubs of the World in 1925 called 'Advertising Is a Vital Force in Our National Life." In October 1929, the head of the U.S.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Bureau of Foreign and Domestic Commerce, Julius Klein, stated "Advertising is the key to world prosperity." This was part of the "unparalleled" collaboration between business and government in the 1920s.
[src:trade-association/advertising] During this era, tobacco companies became major advertisers in order to sell packaged cigarettes.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The tobacco companies pioneered new advertising techniques when they hired Bernays to create positive associations with tobacco smoking.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising was also used as a vehicle for cultural assimilation, encouraging workers to exchange their traditional habits and community structure in favor of a shared "modern" lifestyle.
[src:trade-association/advertising] An important tool for influencing immigrant workers was the American Association of Foreign Language Newspapers (AAFLN).
[src:trade-association/advertising] The AAFLN was primarily an advertising agency but also gained heavily centralized control over much of the immigrant press.
[src:trade-association/advertising] At the turn of the 20th century, advertising was one of the few career choices for women.
[src:trade-association/advertising] As women were responsible for most household purchasing, advertisers and agencies recognized the value of women's insight during the creative process.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In fact, the first American advertising to use a sexual sell was created by a woman – for a soap product.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Although tame by today's standards, the advertisement featured a couple with the message "A skin you love to touch".
[src:trade-association/advertising] Watson contributed applied psychological theory to the field of advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Scott said, "Man has been called the reasoning animal, but he could with greater truthfulness be called the creature of suggestion.
[src:trade-association/advertising] He is reasonable, but he is to a greater extent suggestible".
[src:trade-association/advertising] He demonstrated this through his advertising technique of a direct command to the consumer.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the early 1920s, the first radio stations were established by radio equipment manufacturers, followed by non-profit organizations such as schools, clubs, and civic groups who also set up their own stations.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The rise of mass media communications allowed manufacturers of branded goods to bypass retailers by advertising directly to consumers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This was a major paradigm shift that forced manufacturers to focus on the brand and stimulated the need for superior insights into consumer purchasing, consumption, and usage behavior; their needs, wants, and aspirations.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The earliest radio drama series were sponsored by soap manufacturers and the genre became known as a *soap opera.* Before long, radio station owners realized they could increase advertising revenue by selling 'air-time' in small time allocations, which could be sold to multiple businesses.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By the 1930s, these *advertising spots*, as the packets of time became known, were being sold by the station's geographical sales representatives, ushering in an era of national radio advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By the 1940s, manufacturers began to recognize the way in which consumers were developing personal relationships with their brands in a social/psychological/anthropological sense.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertisers began to use motivational research and consumer research to gather insights into consumer purchasing.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Strong branded campaigns for Chrysler and Exxon/Esso, using insights drawn research methods from psychology and cultural anthropology, led to some of the most enduring campaigns of the 20th century.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the early 1950s, the DuMont Television Network began the modern practice of selling advertisement time to multiple sponsors.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Previously, DuMont had trouble finding sponsors for many of their programs and compensated by selling smaller blocks of advertising time to several businesses.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This eventually became the standard for the commercial television industry in the United States.
[src:trade-association/advertising] However, it was still a common practice to have single sponsor shows, such as The United States Steel Hour.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In some instances the sponsors exercised great control over the content of the show – up to and including having one's advertising agency actually writing the show.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The single sponsor model is much less prevalent now, a notable exception being the Hallmark Hall of Fame.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The late 1980s and early 1990s saw the introduction of cable television and particularly MTV.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Pioneering the concept of the music video, MTV ushered in a new type of advertising: the consumer tunes in *for* the advertising message, rather than it being a by-product or afterthought.
[src:trade-association/advertising] As cable and satellite television became increasingly prevalent, specialty channels emerged, including channels entirely devoted to advertising, such as QVC, Home Shopping Network, and ShopTV Canada.
[src:trade-association/advertising] With the advent of the ad server, online advertising grew, contributing to the "dot-com" boom of the 1990s.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Entire corporations operated solely on advertising revenue, offering everything from coupons to free Internet access.
[src:trade-association/advertising] At the turn of the 21st century, some websites, including the search engine Google, changed online advertising by personalizing ads based on web browsing behavior.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This has led to other similar efforts and an increase in interactive advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Online advertising introduced new opportunities for targeting and engagement, with platforms like Google and Facebook leading the charge.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This shift has significantly altered the advertising landscape, making digital advertising a dominant force in the industry.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The share of advertising spending relative to GDP has changed little despite large changes in media since 1925.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 1925, the main advertising media in America were newspapers, magazines, signs on streetcars, and outdoor posters.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising spending as a share of GDP was about 2.9%.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By 1998, television and radio had become major advertising media; by 2017, the balance between broadcast and online advertising had shifted, with online spending exceeding broadcast.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Nonetheless, advertising spending as a share of GDP was only slightly lower – about 2.4%.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Guerrilla marketing involves unusual approaches such as staged encounters in public places, giveaways of products such as cars that are covered with brand messages, and interactive advertising where the viewer can respond to become part of the advertising message.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This type of advertising is unpredictable, which can cause consumers to buy the product or idea.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This reflects an increasing trend of interactive and "embedded" ads, such as via product placement, having consumers vote through text messages, and various campaigns utilizing social network services such as Facebook or Twitter/X.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In some instances businesses will obtain media by providing equity.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This is known as media for equity, where advertising is not sold, but is instead provided to start-up companies in return for equity.
[src:trade-association/advertising] If the company grows and is sold, the media companies receive cash for their shares.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This practice started in Europe but has become increasingly popular in the US, with businesses such as Uber, Airbnb and Pinterest achieving global growth by using such tactics.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising may be categorized in a variety of ways, including by style, target audience, geographic scope, medium, or purpose.
[src:trade-association/advertising] For example, in print advertising, classification by style can include display advertising (ads with design elements sold by size) vs. classified advertising (ads without design elements sold by the word or line).
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising may be local, national or global.
[src:trade-association/advertising] An ad campaign may be directed toward consumers or to businesses.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The purpose of an ad may be to raise awareness (brand advertising), or to elicit an immediate sale (direct response advertising).
[src:trade-association/advertising] The term **above the line** (ATL) is used for advertising involving mass media; more targeted forms of advertising and promotion are referred to as **below the line** (BTL).
[src:trade-association/advertising] The two terms date back to 1954 when Procter & Gamble began paying their advertising agencies differently from other promotional agencies.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the 2010s, as advertising technology developed, a new term, **through the line** (TTL) began to come into use, referring to integrated advertising campaigns.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Virtually any medium can be used for advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Any situation in which an "identified" sponsor pays to deliver their message through a medium is advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] game in the United States is known as the most prominent advertising event on television – in 2013 it attracted an audience of over 108 million and studies have shown that 50% of those tune in to see the advertisements.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The 2025 game attracted an audience of over 123 million, with a thirty-second ad costing US$8 million.
[src:trade-association/advertising] may be inserted into regular programming through computer graphics.
[src:trade-association/advertising] or used to replace local billboards that are not relevant to the remote broadcast audience.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This technique is especially used in televised sporting events.
[src:trade-association/advertising] is a long-format television commercial, typically five minutes or longer.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The name blends the words "information" and "commercial".
[src:trade-association/advertising] advertisements are broadcast as radio waves from a transmitter to an antenna and thus to a receiving device.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Increasingly radio is transmitted via the internet.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Airtime is purchased from a station or network in exchange for airing the commercials.
[src:trade-association/advertising] While radio has the limitation of being restricted to sound, proponents of radio advertising often cite this as an advantage.
[src:trade-association/advertising] , 82% of people in the US aged 12 and older listened to terrestrial radio in a given week, in 2022.
[src:trade-association/advertising] for the expressed purpose of delivering marketing messages to attract customers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Online ads are delivered by an ad server.
[src:trade-association/advertising] ; which go in a website's news feed and are supposed to improve user experience by being less intrusive.
[src:trade-association/advertising] However, some people argue this practice is deceptive.
[src:trade-association/advertising] , however, advertisers often lease space directly on domain names that generically describe their products.
[src:trade-association/advertising] records that are publicly available at registrar websites.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This is when a product or brand is embedded in entertainment and media.
[src:trade-association/advertising] shoes several times, calling them "classics", because the film is set far in the future.
[src:trade-association/advertising] logos clearly displayed on the front of the vehicles.
[src:trade-association/advertising] , which as a result contained many scenes in which Cadillac cars were used.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Print advertising describes advertising in a printed medium such as a newspaper, magazine, or trade journal.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This encompasses everything from media with a very broad readership base, such as a major national newspaper or magazine, to more narrowly targeted media such as local newspapers and trade journals on very specialized topics.
[src:trade-association/advertising] , which allows private individuals or companies to purchase a small, narrowly targeted ad paid by the word or line.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Another form of print advertising is the display ad, which is generally a larger ad with design elements that typically run in an article section of a newspaper.
[src:trade-association/advertising] , also known as hoardings in some parts of the world, are large structures located in public places which display advertisements to passing pedestrians and motorists.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Most often, they are located on main roads with a large amount of passing motor and pedestrian traffic; however, they can be placed in any location with large numbers of viewers, such as on mass transit vehicles and in stations, in shopping malls or office buildings, and in stadiums.
[src:trade-association/advertising] ) in public places on a temporary basis.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The large outer advertising space aims to entice the observer in, with the product promoted inside.
[src:trade-association/advertising] are generally vehicle mounted billboards or digital screens.
[src:trade-association/advertising] These can be on dedicated vehicles built solely for carrying advertisements and can travel along routes preselected by advertisers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] They can also be specially equipped cargo trucks or, in some cases, large banners strewn from planes.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Some billboard displays are static, while others change; for example, continuously or periodically rotating a set of advertisements.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Mobile displays are used for various situations in metropolitan areas throughout the world, including: target advertising, one-day and long-term campaigns, conventions, sporting events, store openings and similar promotional events, and advertisements from smaller companies.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In-store advertising is any advertisement placed in a retail store.
[src:trade-association/advertising] It includes placement of a product in visible locations in a store, such as at eye level, at the ends of aisles and near checkout counters (a.k.a.
[src:trade-association/advertising] POP – point of purchase display), eye-catching displays promoting a specific product, advertisements in places such as shopping carts and in-store video displays.
[src:trade-association/advertising] , historically known as advertising novelties or advertising specialties.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Industry commentary has noted a shift in the sector from low-cost giveaway items towards more purpose-driven, brand-aligned products intended to support broader marketing strategies and long-term brand development.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising where a celebrity endorses a product and a brand leverages celebrity influence, fame and popularity to gain recognition for their products or to promote specific stores' or products.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertisers often advertise their products when, for example, celebrities share their favorite products or wear clothes by specific brands or designers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Celebrities are often involved in advertising campaigns, appearing in television, digital and print adverts to advertise brands and their products.
[src:trade-association/advertising] have advertised for multiple products including Pepsi, Candies from Kohl's, Twister, NASCAR, and Toyota.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Drones are now used for aerial advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advanced advertising is data-driven advertising, using large quantities of data and precise targeting and measurement tools.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advanced advertising makes it easier for companies who sell ad space to attribute customer purchases to the ads they display or broadcast.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Increasingly, new media approaches are overtaking "traditional" media such as television, radio and newspaper as people shift to using the internet for activities such as reading, watching or listening to the news.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Online advertising began with unsolicited bulk e-mail advertising known as "e-mail spam".
[src:trade-association/advertising] Spam has been a problem for e-mail users since 1978.
[src:trade-association/advertising] As new online communication channels became available, advertising followed.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The first banner ad appeared on the World Wide Web in 1994.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Internet advertising allows companies to target specific audiences, which can improve return on investment.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The rise of the internet resulted in people using search engines to find websites and the emergence of search engine advertising, as companies sought to advertise to consumers online.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Google was founded in 1998 and by the early 2000's had become the most widely used search engine.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 2000 Google launched AdWords, which allowed advertisers to bid, in order for their adverts to appear in paid search results.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Their auction bidding system used factors such as click-through rate and relevance, with advertisers using high quality ads rewarded with better ad placements and lower costs per click (CPC).
[src:trade-association/advertising] In online display advertising, display ads can generate awareness quickly.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Whereas search requires someone to be aware of a need, display advertising can drive awareness of something new, without previous knowledge.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Display can work well for direct response.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Online display advertising is not only used for generating awareness, it can also be used for direct response campaigns.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Mobile phones became a new mass medium in 1998 when the first paid downloadable content appeared on mobile phones in Finland, mobile advertising followed, first launched in Finland in 2000.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 2007, the value of mobile advertising was expected to be $3 billion, with most of this generated via mobile search and video.
[src:trade-association/advertising] By 2025 this had increased to an estimated market size of $262 billion.
[src:trade-association/advertising] More advanced mobile ads include banner ads, coupons, Multimedia Messaging Service picture and video messages, advergames and various engagement marketing campaigns.
[src:trade-association/advertising] One feature driving mobile ads is the 2D barcode (QR code) which replaces the need to type web addresses, and uses the camera in mobile phones to access web content.
[src:trade-association/advertising] 83% of Japanese mobile phone users are active users of 2D barcodes.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Some companies have proposed placing messages or corporate logos on the side of booster rockets and the International Space Station.
[src:trade-association/advertising] An advertising method has emerged called "ARvertising", which uses augmented reality technology.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The emerging technology of drone displays has been used for advertising purposes.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The internet has also had a significant impact on how people watch TV, with many people now choosing to stream TV content at a time that is convenient to them.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This is particularly true of people in younger age groups, with 50% of streaming viewers being aged 35 or less.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the UK, less than half of 16-24 year olds were watching traditional TV in an average week, in 2023-2024.
[src:trade-association/advertising] As a result, companies are increasingly using connected TV (CTV) to advertise, with this being one of the growing media channels.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 2024, it was suggested that ad spend in this class of media was increasing by almost 20% each year, with this type of advertising offering increased targeting opportunities, to improve effectiveness.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The emergence of social networking sites such as Facebook, Instagram, Twitter/X and TikTok has led to companies increasingly using social media for advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 2024, global social media advertising spend was expected to be $247 billion, a 14.3% year on year increase.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In 2025, Alphabet, Meta and Amazon controlled more than 50% of all advertising spend (globally, excluding China).
[src:trade-association/advertising] These technology companies are able to invest heavily in AI optimisation and creative automation which can improve advertising campaign effectiveness and they all have a first-party data infrastructure.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The concept of crowdsourcing has given way to the trend of user-generated advertisements.
[src:trade-association/advertising] User-generated ads are created by people, as opposed to an advertising agency or the company themselves, often resulting from brand sponsored advertising competitions.
[src:trade-association/advertising] For the 2007 Super Bowl, the Frito-Lays division of PepsiCo held the "Crash the Super Bowl" contest, allowing people to create their own Doritos commercials.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Chevrolet held a similar competition for their Tahoe line of SUVs.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Due to the success of the Doritos user-generated ads in the 2007 Super Bowl, Frito-Lays relaunched the competition for the 2009 and 2010 Super Bowl.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The resulting ads were among the most-watched and most-liked Super Bowl ads.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In fact, the winning ad that aired in the 2009 Super Bowl was ranked by the USA Today Super Bowl Ad Meter as the top ad for the year while the winning ads that aired in the 2010 Super Bowl were found by Nielsen's BuzzMetrics to be the "most buzzed-about".
[src:trade-association/advertising] Another example of companies using crowdsourcing successfully is the beverage company Jones Soda that encourages consumers to participate in the label design themselves.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This trend has given rise to several online platforms that host user-generated advertising competitions on behalf of a company.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Founded in 2007, Zooppa has launched ad competitions for brands such as Google, Nike, Hershey's, General Mills, Microsoft, NBC Universal, Zinio, and Mini Cooper.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Crowdsourcing remains controversial, as the long-term impact on the advertising industry is still unclear.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising has gone through five major stages of development: domestic, export, international, multi-national, and global.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Born from the evolutionary stages of global marketing are the three primary and fundamentally different approaches to the development of global advertising executions: exporting executions, producing local executions, and importing ideas that travel.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising research is key to determining the success of an ad in any country or region.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The ability to identify which elements and/or moments of an ad contribute to its success is how economies of scale are maximized.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Once one knows what works in an ad, that idea or ideas can be imported by any other market.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Market research measures, such as Flow of Attention, Flow of Emotion and branding moments provide insight into what is working in an ad in any country or region because the measures are based on the visual, not verbal, elements of the ad.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Companies and organisations have a number of business goals they wish to achieve.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Broadly, advertising is used to help achieve these objectives.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising delivers a message to customers and prospective customers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] A successful advertising campaign initially defines a clear purpose.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This consists of advertising which aims to increase the number of people who know about (recognise and recall) a brand.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This purpose will impact the type of channels/media and ad formats selected to achieve greater brand awareness.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This type of objective can include creating awareness of new features a brand is offering, such as improving the in-store experience.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Typically a broader marketing activity, advertising campaigns can contribute to companies retaining existing customers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Such advertising may promote customer loyalty schemes and can involve showing personalised offers and promotions.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This involves a business or organisation conducting an advertising campaign where the purpose is to collect information such as name and email addresses, which constitutes a 'lead'.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This can involve providing downloadable content or running webinars.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising effectiveness is measured by establishing the cost per lead.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This data is then used for marketing activities with the aim of converting the prospect/lead to become a customer.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Sales promotions are another way to advertise.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Sales promotions are double purposed because they are used to gather information about what type of customers one draws in and where they are, and to jump start sales.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Sales promotions include things like contests and games, sweepstakes, product giveaways, samples coupons, loyalty programs, and discounts.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The ultimate goal of sales promotions is to stimulate potential customers to action.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Hierarchies of effects models attempt to theoretically explain that consumers go through a number of stages, that can be prompted by advertising, before purchasing a product or service.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The marketing mix was proposed by Harvard Business School professor Neil H.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Borden and expanded on, and popularized by professor E.
[src:trade-association/advertising] It consists of four basic elements called the "**four Ps**".
[src:trade-association/advertising] **Product** is the first P representing the actual product.
[src:trade-association/advertising] **Price** represents the process of determining the value of a product.
[src:trade-association/advertising] **Place** represents the variables of getting the product to the consumer such as distribution channels, market coverage and movement organization.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The last P stands for **Promotion** which is the process of reaching the target market and convincing them to buy the product.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The concept of the **four Cs** was introduced as a more customer-driven replacement of the four P's.
[src:trade-association/advertising] There are two theories based on the four Cs: Lauterborn's four Cs (*consumer*, *cost*, *communication*, *convenience*) and Shimizu's four Cs (*commodity*, *cost*, *channel,* *communication)*.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Shimizu expanded the four Cs, to the **7Cs Compass Model** by adding company or competitor, consumer and circumstances, to acknowledge the impact of competition, consumers who are not customers and circumstances beyond a companies control.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising research is a specialized form of research that works to improve the effectiveness and efficiency of advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] It entails numerous forms of research which employ different methodologies.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising research includes pre-testing (also known as copy testing) and post-testing of ads and/or campaigns.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Pre-testing includes a wide range of qualitative and quantitative techniques, including: focus groups, in-depth target audience interviews (one-on-one interviews), small-scale quantitative studies and physiological measurement.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The goal of this research is to better understand how different groups respond to various messages and visual prompts, thereby providing an assessment of how well the advertisement meets its communications goals.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Post-testing employs many of the same techniques as pre-testing, usually with a focus on understanding the change in awareness or attitude attributable to the advertisement.
[src:trade-association/advertising] With the emergence of digital advertising technologies, many firms have begun to continuously post-test ads using real-time data.
[src:trade-association/advertising] This may take the form of A/B split-testing or multivariate testing.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Continuous ad tracking and the Communicus System are competing examples of post-testing advertising research types.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Meanings between consumers and marketers depict signs and symbols that are encoded in everyday objects.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Semiotics is the study of signs and how they are interpreted.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising has many hidden signs and meanings within brand names, logos, package designs, print advertisements, and television advertisements.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Semiotics aims to study and interpret the message being conveyed in (for example) advertisements.
[src:trade-association/advertising] These signs can be images, words, fonts, colors, slogans, or a combination which must be interpreted by the audience or consumer.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The "key to advertising analysis" is the signifier and the signified.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The signifier is the object and the signified is the mental concept.
[src:trade-association/advertising] A product has a signifier and a signified.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The signifier is the color, brand name, logo design, and technology.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The signified has two meanings known as denotative and connotative.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The denotative meaning is the meaning of the product.
[src:trade-association/advertising] A television's denotative meaning might be that it is high definition.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The connotative meaning is the product's deep and hidden meaning.
[src:trade-association/advertising] A connotative meaning of a television would be that it is top-of-the-line.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Apple's iPod commercials, starting in 2003, used a black silhouette of a person that was the age of Apple's target market.
[src:trade-association/advertising] They placed the silhouette in front of a blue screen so that the picture behind the silhouette could be constantly changing.
[src:trade-association/advertising] However, the one thing that stays the same in these ads is that there is music in the background and the silhouette is listening to that music on a white iPod through white headphones.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Through advertising, the white color on a set of earphones now signifies that the music device is an iPod.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The white color signifies almost all of Apple's products.
[src:trade-association/advertising] While advertising can be seen as necessary for economic growth, it is not without social costs.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Unsolicited commercial e-mail and other forms of spam became so common it was considered to be a nuisance, as well as being a financial burden on internet service providers.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertising is increasingly prevalent in public spaces, such as schools, which some critics argue is unethical.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In tandem with these criticisms, the advertising industry has seen low approval rates in surveys and negative cultural portrayals.
[src:trade-association/advertising] A 2021 study of TV advertising found that only a third of advertisers achieved a positive return on investment.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Unsolicited ads have been criticized as attention theft.
[src:trade-association/advertising] One of the common criticisms of advertising is the predominance of advertising foods high in sugar, fat, and salt specifically to children.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Critics claim that food advertisements targeting children are exploitative and are not conducive with nutritional education to help children understand the consequences of their food choices.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Children may not understand that they are being sold something, and may therefore be more impressionable.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Michelle Obama criticized food companies for advertising unhealthy foods to children.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Other criticisms include the influence of advertising on society and that some advertising can deceive.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Cosmetic and health industry advertising has created causes of concern, such as being misleading.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Political advertising has been scrutinized for misinformation, ethics and political bias.
[src:trade-association/advertising] There have been increasing efforts to protect people by regulating the content and influence of advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Some examples include restrictions for advertising alcohol, tobacco or gambling imposed in many countries, as well as bans on advertising to children, in some parts of Europe.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Some advertising regulation focuses heavily on the veracity of claims and as such, there are often tighter restrictions placed around advertisements for food and healthcare products.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The advertising industries within some countries rely less on laws and more on systems of self-regulation.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Advertisers and the media agree on a code of advertising standards that they attempt to uphold.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The general aim of such codes is to ensure that any advertising is 'legal, decent, honest and truthful'.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Some self-regulatory organizations are funded by the industry, but remain independent, with the intent of upholding the standards or codes like the Advertising Standards Authority in the UK.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the UK, most forms of outdoor advertising, are regulated by the UK Town and County Planning system.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The display of some advertisements without consent is a criminal offence liable to a fine of £2,500.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the US, where some communities believe that outdoor advertising is a blight on some landscapes, attempts to ban billboard advertising occurred in the 1960s, leading to the *Highway Beautification Act*.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Cities such as São Paulo have introduced an outright ban.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Some governments restrict the languages that can be used in advertisements, but advertisers may employ tactics to try to avoid them.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In France for instance, advertisers sometimes print English words in bold and French translations in fine print to deal with Article 120 of the 1994 Toubon Law limiting the use of English.
[src:trade-association/advertising] The advertising of pricing information is another topic of concern for governments.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In the United States for instance, it is common for businesses to only mention the existence and amount of applicable taxes at a later stage of a transaction.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In Canada and New Zealand, taxes can be listed as separate items, as long as they are quoted up-front.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In most other countries, the advertised price must include all applicable taxes, enabling customers to easily know how much it will cost them.
[src:trade-association/advertising] According to a 1977 study by David Statt, females process information comprehensively, while males process information through heuristic devices such as procedures, methods or strategies for solving problems, which could effect how they interpret advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Men prefer to have cues to interpret the message, whereas females engage in more creative, associative and imagery-laced interpretation.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Later research found that advertising attempts to persuade men to improve their appearance or performance, whereas its approach to women aims at transformation towards an impossible ideal of female presentation.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Paul Suggett's article "The Objectification of Women in Advertising" discusses the negative impact of portraying unrealistic ideals of female beauty in advertisements on women, as well as men.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Studies show that these expectations on women and young girls can negatively affect their views about their bodies and appearance, although others disagree with these findings.
[src:trade-association/advertising] There are some companies like Dove that are creating commercials to portray more natural women and all forms of beauty, via their Campaign for Real Beauty.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Research by Martin in 2003 revealed that males and females react differently to advertising depending on their mood at the time of ad exposure and the tone of the advertising.
[src:trade-association/advertising] When feeling sad, males prefer happy ads to boost their mood.
[src:trade-association/advertising] In contrast, females prefer happy ads when they are feeling happy.
[src:trade-association/advertising] Susan Wojcicki, author of the article "Ads that Empower Women don't just Break Stereotypes—They're also Effective" discusses how advertising to women has changed since the first Barbie commercial, where a little girl tells the doll that, she wants to be just like her.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Motives for action may be based on political, economic, religious, moral, commercial or common good-based positions.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Groups use varied methods to try to achieve their aims, including lobbying, media campaigns, awareness raising publicity stunts, polls, research, and policy briefings.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Some groups are supported or backed by powerful business or political interests and exert considerable influence on the political process, while others have few or no such resources.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Some have developed into important social, and political institutions or social movements.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Some powerful advocacy groups have been accused of manipulating the democratic system for narrow commercial gain, and in some instances have been found guilty of corruption, fraud, bribery, influence peddling and other serious crimes.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Some groups, generally the ones with less financial resources, may use direct action and civil disobedience, and in some cases are accused of being a threat to the social order or "domestic extremists".
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Research is beginning to explore how advocacy groups use social media to facilitate civic engagement, and collective action.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The early growth of pressure groups was connected to broad economic and political changes in England in the mid-18th century, including political representation, market capitalization, and proletarianization.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The first mass social movement catalyzed around the controversial political figure, John Wilkes.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] As editor of the paper *The North Briton*, Wilkes vigorously attacked the new administration of Lord Bute and the peace terms that the new government accepted at the 1763 Treaty of Paris at the end of the Seven Years' War.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Charged with seditious libel, Wilkes was arrested after the issue of a general warrant, a move that Wilkes denounced as unlawful – the Lord Chief Justice eventually ruled in Wilkes favour.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] As a result of this episode, Wilkes became a figurehead to the growing movement for popular sovereignty among the middle classes – people began chanting, "Wilkes and Liberty" in the streets.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] After a later period of exile, brought about by further charges of libel and obscenity, Wilkes stood for the Parliamentary seat at Middlesex, where most of his support was located.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] This was the first ever sustained social advocacy group – it involved public meetings, demonstrations, the distribution of pamphlets on an unprecedented scale and the mass petition march.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] However, the movement was careful not to cross the line into open rebellion – it tried to rectify the faults in governance through appeals to existing legal precedents and was conceived of as an extra-Parliamentary form of agitation to arrive at a consensual and constitutional arrangement.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The force and influence of this social advocacy movement on the streets of London compelled the authorities to concede to the movement's demands.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Wilkes was returned to Parliament, general warrants were declared as unconstitutional and press freedom was extended to the coverage of Parliamentary debates.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Another important advocacy group that emerged in the late 18th century was the British abolitionist movement against slavery.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Starting with an organised sugar boycott in 1791, it led the second great petition drive of 1806, which brought about the banning of the slave trade in 1807.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] In the opinion of Eugene Black (1963), "...association made possible the extension of the politically effective public.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Modern extra parliamentary political organization is a product of the late eighteenth century [and] the history of the age of reform cannot be written without it.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] From 1815, Britain after victory in the Napoleonic Wars entered a period of social upheaval characterised by the growing maturity of the use of social movements and special-interest associations.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Chartism was the first mass movement of the growing working-class in the world.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] It campaigned for political reform between 1838 and 1848 with the People's Charter of 1838 as its manifesto – this called for universal suffrage and the implementation of the secret ballot, amongst other things.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The labor movement and socialist movement of the late 19th century are seen as the prototypical social movements, leading to the formation of communist and social democratic parties and organisations.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] These tendencies were seen in poorer countries as pressure for reform continued, for example in Russia with the Russian Revolution of 1905 and of 1917, resulting in the collapse of the Czarist regime around the end of the First World War.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] In the post-war period, women's rights, gay rights, peace, civil rights, anti-nuclear and environmental movements emerged, often dubbed the New Social Movements, some of which may be considered "general interest groups" as opposed to special interest groups.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] They led, among other things, to the formation of green parties and organisations influenced by the new left.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Some find in the end of the 1990s the emergence of a new global social movement, the anti-globalization movement.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Some social movement scholars posit that with the rapid pace of globalization, the potential for the emergence of new *type* of social movement is latent—they make the analogy to national movements of the past to describe what has been termed a global citizens movement.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups exist in a wide variety of genres based upon their most pronounced activities.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] In most liberal democracies, advocacy groups tend to use the bureaucracy as the main channel of influence – because, in liberal democracies, this is where the decision-making power lies.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The aim of advocacy groups here is to attempt to influence a member of the legislature to support their cause by voting a certain way in the legislature.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Access to this channel is generally restricted to groups with insider status such as large corporations and trade unions – groups with outsider status are unlikely to be able to meet with ministers or other members of the bureaucracy to discuss policy.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] What must be understood about groups exerting influence in the bureaucracy is; "the crucial relationship here [in the bureaucracy] is usually that between the senior bureaucrats and leading business or industrial interests".
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] This supports the view that groups with greater financial resources at their disposal will generally be better able to influence the decision-making process of government.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The advantages that large businesses have is mainly due to the fact that they are key producers within their countries economy and, therefore, their interests are important to the government as their contributions are important to the economy.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] According to George Monbiot, the influence of big business has been strengthened by "the greater ease with which corporations can relocate production and investment in a global economy".
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] This suggests that in the ever modernising world, big business has an increasing role in influencing the bureaucracy and in turn, the decision-making process of government.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups can also exert influence through the assembly by lobbying.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Groups with greater economic resources at their disposal can employ professional lobbyists to try and exert influence in the assembly.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] An example of such a group is the environmentalist group Greenpeace; Greenpeace (an organisation with income upward of $50,000,000) use lobbying to gain political support for their campaigns.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] They raise issues about the environment with the aim of having their issues translated into policy such as the government encouraging alternative energy and recycling.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The judicial branch of government can also be used by advocacy groups to exert influence.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] In states where legislation cannot be challenged by the courts, like the UK, advocacy groups are limited in the amount of influence they have.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] In states that have codified constitutions, like the US, however, advocacy group influence is much more significant.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] For example, in 1954 the NAACP (National Association for the Advancement of Colored People) lobbied against the Topeka Board of education, arguing that segregation of education based on race was unconstitutional.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] As a result of group pressure from the NAACP, the supreme court unanimously ruled that racial segregation in education was indeed unconstitutional and such practices were banned.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] This is a novel example of how advocacy groups can exert influence in the judicial branch of government.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups can also exert influence on political parties.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The main way groups do this is through campaign finance.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] For instance; in the UK, the conservative parties campaigns are often funded by large corporations, as many of the conservative parties campaigns reflect the interests of businesses.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Bush's re-election campaign in 2004 was the most expensive in American history and was financed mainly by large corporations and industrial interests that the Bush administration represented in government.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Conversely, left-wing parties are often funded by organised labour – when the British Labour Party was formed, it was largely funded by trade unions.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Often, political parties are actually formed as a result of group pressure, for example, the Labour Party in the UK was formed out of the new trade union movement which lobbied for the rights of workers.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups also exert influence through channels that are separate from the government or the political structure such as the mass media and through public opinion campaigning.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups will use methods such as protesting, petitioning and civil disobedience to attempt to exert influence in Liberal Democracies.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Groups will generally use two distinct styles when attempting to manipulate the media – they will either put across their outsider status and use their inability to access the other channels of influence to gain sympathy or they may put across a more ideological agenda.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Traditionally, a prime example of such a group were the trade-unions who were the so-called "industrial" muscle.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Trade-unions would campaign in the forms of industrial action and marches for workers rights, these gained much media attention and sympathy for their cause.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] In the United States, the Civil Rights Movement gained much of its publicity through civil disobedience; African Americans would simply disobey the racist segregation laws to get the violent, racist reaction from the police and white Americans.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] This violence and racism was then broadcast all over the world, showing the world just how one sided the race 'war' in America actually was.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy group influence has also manifested itself in supranational bodies that have arisen through globalisation.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Groups that already had a global structure such as Greenpeace were better able to adapt to globalisation.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Greenpeace, for example, has offices in over 30 countries and has an income of $50 million annually.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Groups such as these have secured the nature of their influence by gaining status as nongovernmental organisations (NGOs), many of which oversee the work of the UN and the EU from their permanent offices in America and Europe.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Group pressure by supranational industries can be exerted in a number of ways: "through direct lobbying by large corporations, national trade bodies and 'peak' associations such as the European Round Table of Industrialists".
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups can influence policies away from the median voter.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] There have been many significant advocacy groups throughout history, some of which could operated with dynamics that could better categorize them as social movements.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] A general theory is that individuals must be enticed with some type of benefit to join an interest group.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] However, the free rider problem addresses the difficulty of obtaining members of a particular interest group when the benefits are already reaped without membership.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] For instance, an interest group dedicated to improving farming standards will fight for the general goal of improving farming for every farmer, even those who are not members of that particular interest group.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Thus, there is no real incentive to join an interest group and pay dues if the farmer will receive that benefit anyway.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] For another example, every individual in the world would benefit from a cleaner environment, but environmental protection interest groups do not receive monetary help from every individual in the world.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] This poses a problem for interest groups, which require dues from their members and contributions in order to accomplish the groups' agendas.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Selective benefits are material, rather than monetary benefits conferred on group members.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] For instance, an interest group could give members free or discounted travel, meals, or periodical subscriptions.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Many trade and professional interest groups tend to give these types of benefits to their members.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] A solidarity incentive is a reward for participation that is socially derived and created out of the act of association.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Examples include "socializing congeniality, the sense of group membership and identification, the status resulting from membership, fun, conviviality, the maintenance of social distinctions, and so on.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] People who join an interest group because of expressive benefits likely joined to express an ideological or moral value that they believe in, such as free speech, civil rights, economic justice, or political equality.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] To obtain these types of benefits, members would simply pay dues, and donate their time or money to get a feeling of satisfaction from expressing a political value.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Also, it would not matter if the interest group achieved their goal; these members would merely be able to say they helped out in the process of trying to obtain their goals, which is the expressive incentive that they got in the first place.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] The types of interest groups that rely on expressive benefits or incentives are environmental groups and groups who claim to be lobbying for the public interest.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Much work has been undertaken by academics attempting to categorize how advocacy groups operate, particularly in relation to governmental policy creation.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] However, this pluralist theory (formed primarily by American academics) reflects a more open and fragmented political system similar to that in countries such as the United States.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] There are three broad perspectives on how special interest groups achieve influence: through quid pro quo exchange, information transmission, and subsidizing policymaking.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Apart from lobbying and other methods of asserting political presence, advocacy groups use social media to attract attention towards their particular cause.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] A study published in early 2012 suggests that advocacy groups of varying political and ideological orientations operating in the United States are using social media to interact with citizens every day.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Another 2012 study argued that advocacy groups use social media to reach audiences unrelated to the communities they help and to mobilize diverse groups of people.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] While these studies show the acceptance of social media use by advocacy groups, populations not affiliated with media advocacy often question the benevolence of social media.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Rather than exclusively fostering an atmosphere of camaraderie and universal understanding, social media can perpetuate power hierarchies.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Since media advocacy groups use social media as a way to boost the narratives of these populations, the effect of social media use can be counteractive to well-intentioned goals.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Instead of directly amplifying the voices and narratives of historically marginalized populations, social media magnifies their concerns through the perspective of individuals with access to the internet.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] Since advocacy groups have the agency to control a community's narrative through a social media post, they have the agency to control the deservedness of a community as well.
[src:trade-association/advocacy-group] That is, the amount of resources or attention a community receives largely depends on the kind of narrative an advocacy group curates for them on social media.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The **American Bar Association** (**ABA**) is a voluntary national bar association of lawyers and law students in the United States, and not specific to any single jurisdiction.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Founded in 1878, the ABA's stated activities are the setting of academic standards for law schools, and the formulation of model ethical codes related to the legal profession.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] As of fiscal year 2017, the ABA had 194,000 dues-paying members, constituting approximately 24.4% of American attorneys.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 1979, half of all lawyers in the U.S. were members of the ABA.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2016, about one third of the 1.3 million practicing lawyers in the U.S. were included in the ABA membership of 400,000, with figures largely unchanged in 2024; Included are "about 150,000 paying members" for 2024–2025, according to *Reuters*.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The organization's national headquarters are in Chicago, Illinois, with a branch office in Washington, D.C..
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The association is affiliated with the law, legal, and professional research sponsoring organization the American Bar Foundation.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA was founded on August 21, 1878, in Saratoga Springs, New York, by 75 lawyers from 20 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 1918, the first women were admitted to the ABA – Judge Mary Belle Grossman of Cleveland and Mary Florence Lathrop of Denver.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Prior to 1943, the ABA did not knowingly admit any African-American members and its discrimination led to the formation in 1937 of the National Lawyers Guild.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Rivers in 1943 and several prominent members threatened to quit as a result and the organization was finally integrated.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA appointed Jill Wine-Banks as its first woman executive director, who served from 1987 to 1990.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Roberta Cooper Ramo was the first female president of the ABA from 1995 to 1996.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2016 ABA introduced a new ethics rule prohibiting attorneys from using sexist, racist and condescending terms.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The rule also prohibits attorneys from engaging in discrimination based on age in the conduct of bar association activities.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] On May 1, 2019, the ABA launched a new membership model aimed at reversing declining membership and revenue.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] As mentioned in "Criticisms", below, and despite ABA's own rule against age-discriminatory conduct, the "experience-based" component of the ABA dues structure is a proxy for age discrimination, imposing significantly higher dues on lawyers as their years in practice increase.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2025, the ABA, as well as some members of the organization, became targets of the Trump administration.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] On February 11, with tens of millions of dollars in its USAID and U.S.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] State Department funding frozen by Executive Order 14169, issued on Trump's first day following re-election, the ABA and other plaintiffs filed a lawsuit which asserts that the administration's actions were arbitrary and a capricious violation of the Administrative Procedure Act.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] District Court for the District of Columbia and assigned to Judge Amir Ali.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Two days later he issued a temporary restraining order, allowing some foreign assistance programs to resume.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] On February 14, Federal Trade Commission chair Andrew N.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Ferguson ordered his roster of political appointees not to renew memberships in the ABA, hold any ABA position, or attend any ABA events.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Harvard*, and violates civil law, while threatening to rescind ABA accreditation authority of U.S. law schools.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA released a statement on March 3, 2025, encouraging members to challenge Trump's actions that it perceives to undermine the courts and the legal profession, with more than 50 smaller bar associations joining the call for solidarity.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] While the ABA strongly condemned the Trump administration's actions; on March 25, *Reuters* reported that "President Donald Trump expanded his attacks on major U.S. law firms" in issuing his fourth executive order targeting a law firm in two months.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA adopts "policy" (organizational positions) on certain legislative and national issues, as voted on by its elected, 589-member House of Delegates.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Its board of governors, with 44 members, has the authority to act for the ABA, consistent with previous action of the House of Delegates, when the House is not in session.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA president, elected to a one-year term, is chief executive officer of the association, while the appointed, longer-serving executive director works as chief operating officer.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The conclusion of the ABA annual meeting, in August, is when a new president takes office, as well as when the main sessions of the House of Delegates take place.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The annual meeting also gives the general membership the opportunity to participate in educational programs and hear speakers address many issues.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Rives, formerly TJAG (The Judge Advocate General of the Air Force), was appointed executive director and chief operating officer (COO).
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Brady was named ABA Executive Director/COO after Rives' retirement in March 2023.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] She joined the ABA staff in 1988 and rose through the ranks at the association before being named deputy executive director in 2022.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The United States Department of Education recognises the Council of the ABA Section on Legal Education and Admissions to the Bar as a professional accrediting agency for law schools in the U.S.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] American law schools that are accredited by the council are termed "approved" by the ABA, which indicates the law school was found to be in compliance with ABA accreditation standards.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] ABA accreditation is important not only because it affects the recognition of the law schools involved, but it also affects a graduate's ability to practice law in a particular state.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Specifically, in most U.S. jurisdictions, graduation from an ABA-accredited law school is prerequisite towards being allowed to sit for that state's bar exam, and even for existing lawyers to be admitted to the bar of another state upon motion.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Even states which recognize unaccredited schools within their borders will generally not recognize such schools from other jurisdictions for purposes of bar admission.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] For law students attending ABA-accredited schools, memberships are available for free.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Students attending non-ABA accredited law schools are permitted to join the ABA as associate members.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA's House of Delegates rejected that proposal in 2023 over concerns it would make admissions offices more dependent on subjective measures such as the prestige of an applicant's college, potentially putting minority applicants at a disadvantage.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2024, the council created a new variance process by which individual law schools may apply for permission to bypass the existing admission test requirement.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] This new process does not require approval from the House of Delegates as it is not part of accreditation standards.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA accreditation process has been widely criticized for failing to ensure that law schools are disclosing accurate post-graduate statistics which may mislead students regarding the post-graduate job market, especially in light of ever-growing student loan debt.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] There are heated debates over requirements placed on law schools by the ABA.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Many states and practitioners believe ABA requirements to be unnecessary, costly, outdated and lacking innovation.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Some legal professionals and academics feel these requirements promote the rising cost of tuition.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The collision of attorney layoffs in 2009, the glut of fresh non-top-tier law graduates without work, and the continued expansion of law schools raised questions on whether the ABA has been too lenient in its accreditation process.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] A non-profit organization, Law School Transparency, called upon the ABA to provide meaningful statistics regarding the employment prospects and salary information of graduates of ABA accredited institutions.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Despite the ongoing controversy surrounding law school accreditation standards and inability of law school graduates to effectively service their educational debt, the ABA continued to approve new law schools.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Since 2014, the ABA has required law schools to disclose more information about their applicants and graduates.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2015, ABA-approved law schools reported that, 10 months after graduation, 70 percent of graduates were employed in long-term, full-time positions where bar passage is required or a J.D. is preferred.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] By 2025, over 87 percent of ABA-approved law school graduates were employed in bar passage required or J.D. advantage jobs.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In May 2019, the ABA Council of the Section of Legal Education and Admissions to the Bar changed the requirement for graduate bar passage rates.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Previously, to remain accredited, schools had to have a 75% bar passage rate for students within 5 years of graduation, with various ways to meet this standard and no law schools having ever been found in violation of the rule.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The new rule requires the 75% bar passage rate be achieved within 2 years with no exceptions.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The change was passed by the Section despite failing a vote in the ABA House of Delegates twice.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Proponents of the change say the increased standard will ensure students are better prepared for passing the bar and for legal practice in general with less students acquiring large student debt without reasonable job opportunities.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Opponents claim this will adversely affect diversity in law schools, which will be forced to increase their admissions standards and required LSAT scores, which in turn will disproportionately affect minority applicants.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Under the new plan, 14 schools will be at risk of losing their accreditation if their bar-passage rates do not improve within two years.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] At the time of the rule change, three law schools were currently in the process of closing, and another school was under probation.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In June 2019, the ABA voted to revoke the accreditation of Thomas Jefferson School of Law in San Diego, California.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 1995 the United States Department of Justice accused the ABA of violating Section 1 of the Sherman Act in its law school accreditation proceedings.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The case was resolved with a consent decree.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2006, the ABA acknowledged that it violated the consent decree and paid DOJ a $185,000 fine.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA Publishing division of the Association publishes a variety of law education and practice resources and monthly magazine, as well as memoirs and works of legal history and fiction under its Ankerwycke imprint, which launched in 2014.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The association publishes a monthly print and digital magazine circulated to all members, the *ABA Journal* (since 1984, formerly *American Bar Association Journal*, 1915–1983).
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Some of these magazines, such as the Business Law Section's "Business Law Today", are available on-line to non-members.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The first such journal was the *Annual Bulletin* of the Comparative Law Bureau, the first comparative law journal in the U.S.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The entities also hold their own meetings, such as the annual Solo Day.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA's Commission on Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity was established in 2007.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA's Criminal Justice Section, specifically the Corrections Committee, focuses on the United States Criminal Justice System and its surrounding laws, policies, and structure.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The Corrections Committee "is pushing to provide greater assistance ... for those reentering society" from prison by pushing law schools and state bar associations to provide opportunities for law students to represent prisoners reentering society.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2017, the ABA's Commission on Women in the Profession released "A Current Glance at Women in the Law", providing research about the status of women in the American legal profession.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The report showed a 6 percent increase in women attorneys over the last decade, with women currently making up 36 percent of the legal profession.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Law schools award 47.3 percent of J.D.s to women, which has been consistent for the past 10 years.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In private practice law firms, women make up less than 22 percent of partners, a 4.2 percent increase over the last 10 years.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In the last decade, there has been a significant growth rate of women in the role of general counsel in Fortune 500 companies, but still women only represent 24.8 percent of Fortune 500 general counsels.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2011, the ABA's House of Delegates passed an anti-bullying resolution that included sexual orientation and gender identity among characteristics that should be protected, along with race, religion, national origin, sex, and disability.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] At the 2013 annual meeting, the ABA's House of Delegates passed a resolution that made it harder for criminal defense lawyers to use the LGBT panic defense, which argues that a crime victim's sexual orientation or gender identity should mitigate the defendant's guilt.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] A hearing in 2009 heard testimony from the ABA that "Sentencing by mandatory minimums is the antithesis of rational sentencing policy".
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In July 2006, an ABA task force under then-ABA president Michael S.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Greco released a report that concluded that George W.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Bush's use of "signing statements" violated the Constitution.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] These are documents attached by the president when signing bills, in which the president expresses an opinion that newly created legal restrictions on the executive branch or president are not binding and need not be enforced or obeyed as written.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] At the 2010 annual meeting, the ABA passed Resolution 111 urging every state, territorial, and tribal government to eliminate legal barriers to civil marriage between two persons of the same sex who are otherwise eligible to marry.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 1948, the ABA began to participate in the federal judicial nomination process by informally submitting its own independent committee evaluations to the United States Senate.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The committee consists of two members from the ninth judicial circuit, one member from each of the other federal judicial circuits and the chair of the committee.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA's board of governors, House of Delegates and officers are not involved with the work of the committee, and it is completely insulated from the rest of the ABA's activities, including its policies.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Although the committee rates prospective nominees, it does not propose, recommend or endorse candidates for nomination to the federal judiciary, as that would compromise its independent evaluative function.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The committee works in strictly-enforced confidentiality, typically evaluating around 60 nominees per year.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Nominees are rated as "well qualified", "qualified" or "not qualified".
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] If the president selects a prospective nominee, the committee chair notifies the White House, the Department of Justice, the members of the Senate Judiciary Committee and the nominee of the committee's rating.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] There are several procedural differences between the committee's investigations of Supreme Court nominees and those of lower courts, notably that investigations of Supreme Court nominees are conducted after the president has submitted a nomination.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Also, there is added scrutiny with Supreme Court nominees, such as teams of law professors examining the legal writings of the prospective justice.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The process has been alleged by some (including the Federalist Society) to have a liberal bias.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] For example, the ABA gave Ronald Reagan's judicial nominees Richard Posner and Frank H.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Easterbrook low "qualified/not qualified" ratings; later, the ABA gave Bill Clinton judicial nominees with similar resumes "well qualified" ratings.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Bush administration announced that it would cease submitting names to the ABA in advance of judicial nominations.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA continued to rate nominees, just not before the names were released publicly.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] During the Obama administration, the ABA was once again given advance notice of judicial nominees for rating.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Bush's policy of not giving the ABA advanced notice of judicial nominees.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Bush's nominees received a 'not qualified' ranking, four of Clinton's nominees, zero of Obama's nominees, and, through December 2018, six of Trump's nominees were rated 'not qualified'.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Supreme Court nominees, Chief Justice John G.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Roberts Jr., Justice Samuel Alito, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Justice Elena Kagan, Justice Neil Gorsuch, Brett Kavanaugh, Amy Coney Barrett, and Ketanji Brown Jackson all received the same "well qualified" rating.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 2001 a study "found that nominees confirmed to the federal appeals courts with prior judicial experience fared about the same before the bar association whether they were nominated by the first President George Bush or President Bill Clinton.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Candidates nominated by a Democratic president were 15 percent more likely to receive a "well qualified" ranking than a similarly qualified candidate nominated by a Republican president.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The Standing Committee conducted evaluations on prospective nominees to the lower federal courts, on a pre-nomination basis and at the request of the President of the United States, during 1953–2000 and 2009–2016.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Bush ended its long-standing veto power over nominees in 2001, claiming a liberal bias. and the ABA conducted evaluations after the president had submitted the names of nominees to the Senate, prior to any action by the Senate Judiciary Committee, during through 2008.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Its veto status was restored by President Barack Obama in March 2009.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In March 2017, the Standing Committee resumed the conducting its evaluations on a post-nomination basis.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA judicial nominee rating process drew additional attention during the first Trump administration.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Through June 2019, six of President Trump's nominees were rated "not qualified." Three of those were ranked unanimously not qualified, which had only occurred twice previously since the George H.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] These ratings added further fuel to conservatives' arguments of bias in the nominee rating process.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Republicans argued that members of the Committee on the Federal Judiciary have allowed their personal liberal political leanings to influence their ratings under the category of judicial temperament.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Department of Justice announced that the Trump administration would no longer cooperate with the ABA's vetting of judicial nominees.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The Justice Department said it would no longer provide the ABA special access to judicial nominees, curtailing the ABA's ability to vet new nominations made by President Trump.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Throughout its history, the ABA has faced a range of criticism for different issues, including for its past stances regarding race, lack of diversity, and for policy positions.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] This led to a resolution that August, in which the body of the organization chose to reinstate the memberships of those three lawyers, but require any further Black applicants to include their race on their application.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The policy changed in 1943, but no African American lawyers joined until 1950.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] In 1925, African-American lawyers formed the National Bar Association at a time when the ABA would not allow them to be members.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] As of 2024, the National Bar Association had about 67,000 members and 84 chapters.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Since the 2010s, the ABA has drawn some criticism, mainly from Republicans, for taking positions on controversial public policy topics, such as abortion, gun control, and same-sex marriage.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA's official position in favor of abortion rights led to the formation of an alternative organization for lawyers in 1993, the National Lawyers for Life, now the National Lawyers Association.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The Federalist Society previously sponsored a twice-a-year publication called "ABA Watch" that reports on the political activities of the ABA.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Writing for the *Forbes* website, Mark A.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Cohen criticized the ABA for failing to keep the practice of law in America up with the changing demands of modern society.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Cohen also criticized the ABA for opposing regulatory reform that would help increase access to affordable legal services for those in need and for engaging in protectionism when some legal services could be performed by paralegals and other non-lawyer professionals at a lower cost.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Eighty percent of Americans cannot afford legal services and the ABA has failed to embrace alternative legal delivery methods that could address this problem.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] The ABA also failed to address rules that prohibit some online legal referral websites when it updated the Model Rules regarding Communication Concerning a Lawyer's Services.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] Each August, the ABA holds an annual meeting in different cities that consists of speeches, CLE classes, gatherings, and the ABA Expo.
[src:trade-association/american-bar-association] At the meeting, the recipient of the association's highest honor, the American Bar Association Medal, is announced.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Anti-competitive behavior refers to actions taken by a business or organization to limit, restrict or eliminate competition in a market, usually in order to gain an unfair advantage or dominate the market.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] These practices are often considered illegal or unethical and can harm consumers, other businesses and the broader economy.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Anti-competitive behavior is used by business and governments to lessen competition within the markets so that monopolies and dominant firms can generate supernormal profit margins and deter competitors from the market.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Therefore, it is heavily regulated and punishable by law in cases where it substantially affects the market.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Anti-competitive behavior can be grouped into two classifications.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Horizontal restraints regard anti-competitive behavior that involves competitors at the same level of the supply chain.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] These practices include mergers, cartels, collusions, price-fixing, price discrimination and predatory pricing.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] On the other hand, the second category is vertical restraint which implements restraints against competitors due to anti-competitive practice between firms at different levels of the supply chain e.g. supplier-distributor relationships.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] These practices include exclusive dealing, refusal to deal/sell, resale price maintenance and more.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Horizontal integration can result in economies of scale, economies of density and be anti-competitive.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] When two companies with similar products or product characteristics merge horizontally, there is less competition.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Horizontal mergers can also easily lead to a monopoly, reducing consumers' choices and indirectly harming consumers' interests.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Vertical integration can result in economies of scope and reduce the hold-up problem and be anti-competitive.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] In absence of perfect competition, the Chicago school of economics argues that vertical integration may be pro-competitive by reducing double marginalization.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Unfair competition includes a number of areas of law involving acts by one competitor or group of competitors which harm another in the field, and which may give rise to criminal offenses and civil causes of action.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] Various unfair business practices such as fraud, misrepresentation, and unconscionable contracts may be considered unfair competition, if they give one competitor an advantage over others.
[src:trade-association/anti-competitive-practices] In the European Union, each member state must regulate unfair business practices in accordance with the principles laid down in the Unfair Commercial Practices Directive, subject to transitional periods.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] The organisation, along with Odex, gained considerable prominence in 2007 due to Odex's legal actions against Internet users in Singapore, which were ultimately rejected by the Court in January 2008.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] Up to date, the AVPAS is known to have created a website which features the Odex Clarification Article on their homepage, has images of bootlegged anime and Japanese video CDs and contains a list of authorised titles.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] According to the "Odex Clarification Article" on the AVPAS website, the AVPAS has also been said to have authorised Odex to carry out demands of money from anime downloaders.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] The title "AVPAS" may mislead people into believing that AVPAS is a government organization or an organization registered with the Registry of Societies (ROS).
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] The AVPAS is also not a commercial entity by itself (not registered with ACRA) but is registered by NETROASIA PTE LTD, the "technical admin" for ODEX.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] Netizens virtually unanimously agree that they did not even know about the existence of AVPAS before the Odex Saga.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] The domain name for the AVPAS website was registered in April 2007, three months before Odex started the saga in July to September 2007.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] About its sudden prominence in mid-2007, which coincided with Odex's rise to notoriety among Netizens, there have been concerns raised regarding the legitimacy and purpose of AVPAS, especially since its main committee is dominated by the Odex directors.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] The AVPAS website appears to have ceased from being updated since 31 August 2007.
[src:trade-association/anti-video-piracy-association-of-singapore] Despite being self-dubbed the Anti Video Piracy Association of Singapore, the AVPAS does not seem to be interested in monitoring or combating the copyright violation of non-anime or non-Japanese films.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The history of competition law reaches back to the Roman Empire.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The business practices of market traders, guilds, and governments have always been subject to scrutiny, and sometimes severe sanctions.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Since the late 20th century, competition law has become increasingly global.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The two largest and most influential systems of competition regulation are United States antitrust law, named after the **trust busting** of monopolistic trusts, and European Union competition law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] National and regional competition authorities across the world have formed international support and enforcement networks.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Modern competition law has historically evolved on a national level to promote and maintain fair competition in markets principally within the territorial boundaries of nation-states.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] National competition law usually does not cover activity beyond territorial borders unless it has significant effects at the nation-state level.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Countries may allow for extraterritorial jurisdiction in competition cases based on so-called "effects doctrine".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The protection of international competition is governed by international competition agreements.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law is the field of law that promotes and maintains market competition by regulating anti-competitive practices by companies.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In some jurisdictions, such as the United States, competition law is known as antitrust law because of the historical practice of "trust busting" monopolistic trusts.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It is sometimes also known by reference to its functions, for example, as "anti-monopoly law".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The aims of competition law are to combat economic cartels, prevent market abuse, regulate mergers and acquisitions, encourage innovation, protect consumers, and increase overall economic productivity.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law is rooted in the field of industrial organisation in economics, which studies the interaction between market structure, firm behaviour, and market power, including factors such as barriers to entry, economies of scale, and network effects.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] To control market power, judges and other legal officials have to rely on economic analysis, often relying upon or working with economists to do so.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Early forms of competition law were enacted during the Roman Republic and, later, the Roman Empire.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In continental Europe, competition principles developed in the medieval *lex mercatoria*, while Medieval England also enacted a number of statutes controlling trade practices, with the common law courts creating a number of competition law doctrines that remain to this day.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Major developments to competition law occurred with the growing rise of the market economy, industrialization, and modern capitalism.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Throughout the 18th and 19th centuries, the idea that dominant private companies or legal monopolies could excessively restrict trade led to legal reforms in Europe.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] However, following the Panic of 1873, ideas of competition lost favor, and it was felt that companies had to co-operate by forming cartels to withstand huge pressures on prices and profits.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] While the development of competition law stalled in Europe during the late 19th century, in 1889 Canada enacted what is considered the first competition statute of modern times.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The *Act for the Prevention and Suppression of Combinations formed in restraint of Trade* was passed one year before the United States enacted the Sherman Act of 1890.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] During the early 20th century, legal trusts were employed by business conglomerates to establish monopolies, which led to the development of "antitrust law" in the United States.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] As of 2020, over 140 competition law regimes have been established.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] A majority of these competition law systems were adopted in the past 30 years, following the collapse of the Soviet Union and the expansion of the European Union.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Currently competition authorities of many states closely co-operate, on an everyday basis, with foreign counterparts in their enforcement efforts, in such key areas as information and evidence sharing.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The English common law of restraint of trade is sometimes regarded as the direct predecessor to modern competition law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] English courts subsequently decided a range of cases which gradually developed competition related case law, which eventually were transformed into statute.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] For example, in 1889, Canada enacted what is considered the first competition statute of modern times: The Act for the Prevention and Suppression of Combinations formed in restraint of Trade.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] A year later, the United States enacted the Sherman Act of 1890.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Modern competition law comprises both national and international sources of law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] National competition law usually does not have extraterritorial jurisdiction, unless the economic activity has had a significant national impact, a principle known as the *effects doctrine*.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] International competition law, such as European Union competition law, may have cross-jurisdictional or supranational effect, which may include criminal sanctions.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In 1947, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) was adopted.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In 1994, the World Trade Organization (WTO) was created, establishing a range of limited provisions on various cross-border competition issues on a sector specific basis.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Various proposals have been made historically for the establishment of a global antitrust code, but there remains, at present, no global competition law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] While incapable of enforcement itself, the International Competition Network (ICN) is a way for national authorities to coordinate their own enforcement activities.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] For competition law to intervene into business activity, there must be a significant threat to market competition, consumer welfare, or economic efficiency.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law aims to control a number of business practices, including monopolies and market dominance, abusive conduct, mergers and acquisitions (including horizontal and vertical agreements), and subsidies.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] An early stage in assessing competition law cases is the determination of the relevant market in which competition occurs, for the purposes of microeconomic analysis of factors such as market elasticity, price, and substitute goods.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Under the supranational EU law, a relevant market is the intersection of both the relevant product market and the relevant geographic market.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The SSNIP test is usually used to define markets via assessment of demand-side substitution.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] After defining the market, the courts may inquire as to whether a monopolization (in US law) or market dominance (in EU law) has arisen.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In the United States, monopoly pricing is not inherently regulated, whereas EU law considers it an antitrust offence.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Even where there is no monopolistic or dominant abuse, a company may be sanctioned if they acted abusively, for example, in collusion or cartelism.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition laws across jurisdictions also prohibit certain categories of abusive conduct, although the categories may differ by jurisdiction, and the list of prohibited conduct are often variable and open to new additions.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Forms of abuse relating directly to pricing include price exploitation.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It is difficult to prove at what point a dominant firm's prices become "exploitative" and this category of abuse is rarely found.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] A rarer issue is that of predatory pricing, the practice of dropping prices of a product so much that one's smaller competitors cannot cover their costs and fall out of business, although it is not impossible for such practices to be found.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Commission,* a broadband internet company was forced to pay $13.9 million for dropping its prices below its own production costs.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It had "no interest in applying such prices except that of eliminating competitors", and it was being cross-subsidized to capture the majority share of a booming market.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] A third category of pricing abuse is price discrimination.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] An example of this could be a company offering rebates to industrial customers who export their sugar, but not to customers who are selling their goods in the same market.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Collusion is a deceitful agreement or secret cooperation between two or more parties to limit open competition by deceiving, misleading or defrauding others of their legal right.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Collusion is not always considered illegal.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It can be used to attain objectives forbidden by law; for example, by defrauding or gaining an unfair market advantage.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It is an agreement among firms or individuals to divide a market, set prices, limit production or limit opportunities.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It can involve "price or wage fixing, kickbacks, or misrepresenting the independence of the relationship between the colluding parties".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In legal terms, all acts effected by collusion are considered void.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] A cartel is a group of independent market participants who collaborate with each other and avoid competing with each other in order to improve their profits and dominate the market.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] They seek to limit competition, fix prices, and increase prices by creating artificial shortages through low production quotas, stockpiling, and marketing quotas.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Cartel behaviors can be either legal or illegal, but jurisdictions frequently consider cartelization to be anti-competitive behavior, leading them to outlaw or curtail cartel practices.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Anti-trust law targets cartel behavior in markets.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law regulates mergers and acquisitions prospectively rather than retrospectively in order to prevent potential monopolies and market domination, with companies intending to merge often needing to gain authorization from the state before they can do so.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] When assessing whether a merger or acquisition can be allowed, courts and other officials consider whether there will be a significant effect on competition.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] This is often done through the consideration of empirical evidence.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Although mergers can produce economic benefits such as reduced transaction costs and increased economies of scale, economies of scope, and economies of density, they also result in the concentration of economic power.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Another possible defense might be that the firm which is being taken over is about to fail or go insolvent, and so the resulting competitive state would not be lessened.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] This is known as the "failing firm defense" and has been a regular feature of the U.S.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Horizontal Merger Guidelines since 1982.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Mergers vertically in the market are rarely of concern, although in *AOL/Time Warner* the European Commission required that a joint venture with a competitor Bertelsmann be ceased.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] EU authorities have also focused on the effect of conglomerate mergers, where companies acquire a large portfolio of related products, though without necessarily dominant shares in any individual market.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Bid rigging in public procurement is often illegal, across jurisdictions, in corruption law and often competition law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law may act to restrict the kinds of contracts that can be formed within parties, prohibiting anticompetitive practices such as exclusive dealing retail agreements.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law may restrict occupational licensing.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Certification bodies, for example, can engage also anti-competitive actions, via medical certification bodies reducing competition in health care and thus worsening health economics and health care quality.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Non-compete clauses may also be illegal in competition law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law has become increasingly intertwined with intellectual property, such as copyright, trademarks, patents, industrial design rights and in some jurisdictions trade secrets.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] It is believed that promotion of innovation through enforcement of intellectual property rights may both promote and limit competitiveness.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The question then turns on whether it is legal to acquire monopoly through accumulation of intellectual property rights, In which case the judgment decides between giving preference to intellectual property rights or to competitiveness.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Defences to competition law litigation include ones grounded in constitutional rights (e.g. the US Noerr-Pennington doctrine), sovereign immunity (e.g. the US Parker immunity doctrine), and copyright misuse.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition and antitrust law can require a large conglomerate to be broken up into separate smaller companies.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] For example, the United States required American Telephone & Telegraph (AT&T) and Standard Oil to break up.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Additional approaches to prevent monopoly profits include local-loop unbundling, merger control and monopoly profits taxes.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Across many jurisdictions, a broad principle of competition law that has been applied is the "consumer welfare standard", regards the impact of business practices on consumer welfare as an important if not decisive factor in determining whether to find against the business.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Despite its name, the consumer welfare standard, as originally expressed by conservative legal scholar Robert Bork, does not strictly aim to maximise consumer welfare but the welfare of both producers and consumers.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The use of the consumer welfare standard as a decisive test for whether the law should intervene has been criticised for inappropriately restricting the scope of competition law to effects on prices to consumers instead of more broadly considering issues of fairness, efficiency, and justice.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Today, most jurisdictions agree that the consumer welfare standard is not solely decisive in competition law cases but is one of a number of factors the courts should consider.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The application of competition law also balances between a number of factors beyond a firm's market share or the mere existence of a monopoly, such as the extent to which the firm abuses its monopoly power or to which consumers are paying excessive prices.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Under EU law, for example, very large market shares raise a rebuttable presumption that a firm is dominant.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] If a firm has a dominant position, then there is "a special responsibility not to allow its conduct to impair competition on the common market".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Another deciding factor in determining an abusive monopoly is if the firm behaves "to an appreciable extent independently of its competitors, customers and ultimately of its consumer".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Modern economists and competition lawyers recognise that market failure may occur for a number of reasons and generally agree that intervention is justified if government failure can be avoided.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Economists acknowledge that perfect competition is seldom observed in the real world and so aim for what is called "workable competition".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Contemporary economic developments have challenged conventional industrial organisation models and the efficacy of conventional competition law tools.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] At the same time, contemporary large platform companies engage in complex and multidimensional strategic choices that can be difficult to subject to analytical or regulatory efforts.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] For example, Amazon and Alibaba can change market structure by connecting geographically dispersed buyers and suppliers through centralised infrastructure, imposing terms of participation that privately regulate the market structure and the governance of the platform itself.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In many of Asia's developing countries, including India, Competition law is considered a tool to stimulate economic growth.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In Korea and Japan, the competition law prevents certain forms of conglomerates.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In addition, competition law has promoted fairness in China and Indonesia as well as international integration in Vietnam.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Hong Kong's Competition Ordinance came into force in the year 2015.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] During India's economic liberalization, the Government of India enacted competition laws such as the Monopolies and Restrictive Trade Practices Act of 1969, which became obsolete in 1991 and replaced by the Competition Act, 2002.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The Competition Commission of India, is the quasi judicial body established for enforcing provisions of the 2002 act.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The Anti Monopoly Law of China came into effect in 2008.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] For years, it was enforced by three different branches of government, but since 2018 its enforcement has been the responsibility of the State Administration for Market Regulation.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The *People's Daily* reported that the law had generated 11 billion RMB of penalties between 2008 and 2018.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] As part of the creation of the ASEAN Economic Community, the member states of the Association of South-East Asian Nations (ASEAN) pledged to enact competition laws and policies by the end of 2015.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Today, all ten member states have general competition legislation in place.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Section 1 of the Sherman Act declared illegal "every contract, in the form of trust or otherwise, or conspiracy, in restraint of trade or commerce among the several States, or with foreign nations." Section 2 prohibits monopolies, or attempts and conspiracies to monopolize.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Following the enactment in 1890 US court applies these principles to business and markets.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Courts applied the Act without consistent economic analysis until 1914, when it was complemented by the Clayton Act which specifically prohibited exclusive dealing agreements, particularly tying agreements and interlocking directorates, and mergers achieved by purchasing stock.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] From 1915 onwards the *rule of reason* analysis was frequently applied by courts to competition cases.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] However, the period was characterized by the lack of competition law enforcement.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] From 1936 to 1972 courts' application of antitrust law was dominated by the *structure-conduct-performance* paradigm of the Harvard School.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] From 1973 to 1991, the enforcement of antitrust law was based on efficiency explanations as the Chicago School became dominant, and through legal writings such as Judge Robert Bork's book *The Antitrust Paradox*.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Since 1992 game theory has frequently been used in antitrust cases.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] With the Hart–Scott–Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act of 1976, mergers and acquisitions came into additional scrutiny from U.S. regulators.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Under the act, parties must make a pre-merger notification to the U.S.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Department of Justice and Federal Trade Commission prior to the completion of a transaction.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] As of February 2, 2021, the FTC reduced the Hart-Scott-Rodino reporting threshold to $92 million in combined assets for the transaction.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Canada's competition laws are primarily governed by the Competition Act, a federal statute that regulates business practices to maintain fair competition in the marketplace.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The Act includes both criminal and civil provisions aimed at preventing anti-competitive behavior such as conspiracies, bid-rigging, abuse of dominance, and deceptive marketing.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The Competition Bureau, an independent law enforcement agency, administers and enforces the Act, with cases adjudicated by the Competition Tribunal and courts.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The evolution of competition law in Canada dates back to the *Anti-Combines Act* of 1889, one of the earliest antitrust laws worldwide, which prohibited business conspiracies and agreements that restrained trade.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Over time, this early law was replaced and updated by various laws including the *Combines Investigation Acts* of the early 20th century.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The modern *Competition Act* replaced the *Combines Investigation Act* in 1986, introducing provisions for civil review of mergers and anti-competitive practices under a balance of probabilities standard, along with maintaining criminal sanctions for serious offenses like conspiracy and bid-rigging.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Since then, the Act has undergone multiple amendments to improve enforcement, clarify provisions, and adapt to new market challenges.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] While initially enforcement was exclusive to government authorities, more recent amendments have allowed for limited private rights of action.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The Competition Act and its enforcement framework emphasize preventing undue lessening of competition while balancing economic efficiency and consumer protection.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Competition law gained new recognition in Europe in the inter-war years, with Germany enacting its first anti-cartel law in 1923, followed by Sweden and Norway adopting similar laws in 1925 and 1926, respectively.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] However, with the Great Depression of 1929 competition law disappeared from Europe and was only revived following the Second World War.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] During this period, the United Kingdom and Germany, following pressure from the United States, became the first European countries to adopt fully fledged competition laws.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] At a regional level EU competition law has its origins in the European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC) agreement between France, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg and Germany in 1951 following the Second World War.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The agreement aimed to prevent Germany from re-establishing dominance in the production of coal and steel as it was felt that this dominance had contributed to the outbreak of the war.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Article 65 of the agreement banned cartels and article 66 made provisions for concentrations, or mergers, and the abuse of a dominant position by companies.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] This was the first time that competition law principles were included in a plurilateral regional agreement and established the trans-European model of competition law.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] In 1957 competition rules were included in the Treaty of Rome, also known as the EC Treaty, which established the European Economic Community (EEC).
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The Treaty of Rome established the enactment of competition law as one of the main aims of the EEC through the "institution of a system ensuring that competition in the common market is not distorted".
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The two central provisions on EU competition law were article 85, which prohibited anti-competitive agreements, subject to some exemptions, and article 86 prohibiting the abuse of a dominant position.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The treaty also established principles on competition law for member states, with article 90 covering public undertakings, and article 92 making provisions on state aid.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Regulations on mergers were not included, as member states could not establish consensus on the issue at the time.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Today, the Treaty of Lisbon prohibits anti-competitive agreements in Article 101(1), including price fixing.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] According to Article 101(2) any such agreements are automatically void.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Article 102 prohibits the abuse of dominant position, such as price discrimination and exclusive dealing.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Regulation 139/2004/EC governs mergers between firms.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] The general test is whether a concentration (i.e. merger or acquisition) with a community dimension (i.e. affects a number of EU member states) might significantly impede effective competition.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Articles 106 and 107 provide that member states' right to deliver public services may not be obstructed, but that otherwise public enterprises must adhere to the same competition principles as companies.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Article 107 lays down a general rule that the state may not aid or subsidize private parties in distortion of free competition and provides exemptions for charities, regional development objectives and in the event of a natural disaster.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] Leading ECJ cases on competition law include *Consten & Grundig v Commission* and *United Brands v Commission*.
[src:trade-association/antitrust] This low ranking somehow explains the low employment and low incomes in Armenia.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] The **Colombian Association of Phonogram Producers** (Spanish: *Asociación Colombiana de Productores de Fonogramas*, **ASINCOL**) was a trade group representing the recording industry in Colombia.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] ASINCOL was responsible for music recording sales certification in Colombia and was list as the International Standard Recording Code (ISRC) agency for Colombia until October 2008.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] It was later closed and no local ISRC agency was list in Colombia from November 2008 to July 2021.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] In 2022, the Colombian Association of Performers and Phonogram Producers (Spanish: *Asociación Colombiana de Intérpretes y Productores Fonográficos*, ACINPRO) replaced it as the local ISRC agency for that country.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] ASINCOL was responsible for awarding music recording certifications in Colombia until the organization closed.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] The certification levels for albums until 2000 were 30,000 for gold and 60,000 for Platinum.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] Due to low sales, the levels were lowered in 2004 to 10,000 for Gold and 20,000 for Platinum.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] In 2007 the lower levels for international repertoire were introduced, requiring 5,000 units for Gold and 10,000 for Platinum, while the domestic levels remained unchanged.
[src:trade-association/asociación-colombiana-de-productores-de-fonogramas] ASINCOL also certified music videos, with certification levels of 5,000 for Gold and 10,000 for Platinum.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] A **trade association**, also known as an **industry trade group**, **business association**, **sector association**, **industry consortium** or **industry body**, is an organization founded and funded by businesses that operate in a specific industry.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Through collaboration between companies within a sector, a trade association coordinates public relations activities such as advertising, education, publishing and, especially, lobbying and political action.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Associations may offer other services, such as producing conferences, setting industry standards, industry self-regulation, holding networking or charitable events, or offering classes or educational materials.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Many associations are non-profit organizations governed by bylaws and directed by officers who are also members.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Trade associations and other industry groups are politically influential in the United States, United Kingdom, and other countries, lobbying elected officials, regulators, and other policymakers.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] They also invest heavily in publishing, advertising, and other forms of issue advocacy.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] One of the primary purposes of trade groups, particularly in the United States, is to attempt to influence public policy in a direction favorable to the group's members.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] It can take the form of contributions to the campaigns of political candidates and parties through political action committees (PACs); contributions to "issue" campaigns not tied to a candidate or party; and lobbying legislators to support or oppose particular legislation.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] In addition, trade groups attempt to influence the activities of regulatory bodies.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] In the U.S., direct contributions by PACs to candidates are required to be disclosed to the Federal Election Commission or state and local election overseers; are considered public information; and have registration requirements for lobbyists (lobbyist for the FEC).
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Even so, it can be difficult to trace the funding for issue and non-electoral campaigns.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Trade associations and other industry groups are also politically influential in the United Kingdom, including pro-business lobbying on trade and other issues.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Trade association lobbying is common across the European Union (EU).
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Between February 2024 and February 2025, the 162 largest corporations and trade associations collectively spent €343 million on lobbying EU legislators and officials.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] In Slovenia, the government's approach to consulting business associations has been noted by the European Commission as a good practice example.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Trade associations are heavily involved in publishing activities in print and online.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Examples of trade associations that publish a comprehensive range of media include the European Wind Energy Association (EWEA), Association of British Travel Agents (ABTA) and the Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Industry trade groups sometimes produce advertisements, just as normal corporations do.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] However, whereas typical advertisements are for a specific corporate product, such as a specific brand of cheese or toilet paper, industry trade groups advertisements generally are targeted to promote the views of an entire industry.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] These ads mention only the industry's products as a whole, painting them in a positive light in order to have the public form positive associations with that industry and its products.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] For example, in the US the advertising campaign "Beef.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] It's what's for dinner" is used by the National Cattlemen's Beef Association to promote a positive image of beef in the public consciousness.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] These are adverts targeted at specific issues.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] For example, in the US in the early 2000s the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) began running advertisements before films that advocate against movie piracy over the Internet.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Trade associations have faced frequent criticism due to allegations that they operate not as profit-making organizations, but rather as fronts for cartels involved in anti-competitive practices and price fixing.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Critics contend that these associations engage in activities such as price-fixing, the creation and maintenance of barriers to entry in the industry, and other subtle self-serving actions that are detrimental to the public interest.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] These criticisms raise concerns about the true nature and intentions of trade associations, questioning their commitment to fair competition and the welfare of the broader economy.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] For instance, he said that under the guise of "standard setting", trade associations representing the established players in an industry can set rules that make it harder for new companies to enter a market.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] In September 2007, the German trade association for Fachverband Verbindungs- und Befestigungstechnik (VBT) and five fastener companies were fined 303 million euros by the European Commission for operating cartels in the markets for fasteners and attaching machines in Europe and worldwide.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] In one of the cartels, the YKK Group, Coats plc, the Prym group, the Scovill group, A.
[src:trade-association/trade-association] Raymond, and Berning & Söhne "agreed [...] on coordinated price increases in annual 'price rounds' with respect to 'other fasteners' and their attaching machines, in the framework of work circles organised by VBT".
